      <h1 class="blog-title">Reposition: Get the Crop Right on Every Photo</h1>

      <p class="blog-meta">Feature &nbsp;&bull;&nbsp; 4 min read</p>

      <div class="blog-body">

        <p>Legacy Odyssey is a digital baby book — built as a real website at your child's own .com domain. Your baby gets their name as a website. Parents fill in milestones, photos, and letters through the iOS &amp; Android app. Family visits the book at your-childs-name.com, straight from any browser. Password-protected. $29 for the first year.</p>

        <p>Reposition is a small tool that fixes a common annoyance: when a photo gets cropped on the website and the part that matters — usually the face — ends up cut off. With Reposition, you decide what stays in frame.</p>

        <hr>

        <h2>What it is</h2>

        <p>Different spots in the book show photos at different shapes — a wide hero banner on the Welcome page, square cards in a gallery, and so on. To fit those shapes, the site crops your photo automatically. Most of the time that's fine. Sometimes it isn't: a tall photo gets cropped to a wide banner and trims off the top of someone's head.</p>

        <p>Reposition lets you set the <strong>focal point</strong> — the spot the crop centers on. You drag a dot onto the most important part of the photo, and the book keeps that part in view wherever the photo appears.</p>

        <p>You'll find it on photos throughout the editor — the Welcome hero photo, Birth Story, Month by Month, Our Family, Celebrations, and more — in both the iOS and Android app and the web editor.</p>

        <hr>

        <h2>Why it matters</h2>

        <p>A baby book lives and dies on its photos. One beautiful shot with the face cropped out of the banner can quietly undercut the whole page. Before Reposition, the only fix was to re-crop the image somewhere else and re-upload it. Now you nudge a dot and you're done — and your original photo stays untouched. It's the difference between "close enough" and exactly right.</p>

        <hr>

        <h2>How to use it, step by step</h2>

        <h3>1. Add or open a photo</h3>

        <p>In any editor that has a photo — start with the Welcome page's hero photo, since it's the most prominent — make sure a photo is in place.</p>

        <h3>2. Tap Reposition</h3>

        <p>Below the photo, tap the <strong>⤢ Reposition</strong> button. (On photos used as a hero or banner, it may read "Reposition photo (fix cropping)".) A window opens with your photo on the left and a small <strong>Preview on your site</strong> panel on the right.</p>

        <h3>3. Drag the dot onto what matters</h3>

        <p>Drag the dot onto the most important part of the photo — usually the face. As you move it, the preview panel updates live, showing you exactly how the photo will sit on the website at its real shape. What's under the dot is what stays centered.</p>

        <h3>4. Save</h3>

        <p>Tap <strong>Save position</strong>. The crop updates on the public book, and your editor preview updates too, so you can see the result right away. Want to tweak it later? Open Reposition again and move the dot — there's no limit on changing it.</p>

        <hr>

        <h2>A few tips</h2>

        <ul>
          <li><strong>Pick the face.</strong> When in doubt, put the dot on the baby's face. That's almost always the part you don't want cropped.</li>
          <li><strong>Watch the preview, not the picker.</strong> The left side shows your whole photo; the right side shows the actual crop the website will use. Trust the preview.</li>
          <li><strong>Hero photos benefit most.</strong> Wide banners crop the hardest, so the Welcome hero photo is the first place to check.</li>
          <li><strong>Your original is safe.</strong> Reposition only changes where the crop centers. It never alters or re-saves your photo.</li>
        </ul>

        <hr>

        <h2>An example</h2>

        <p>The book is for Sophia Smith at sophiasmith.com.</p>

        <p>Dad uploads a gorgeous vertical photo of Sophia for the Welcome page — but the page shows the hero as a wide banner, and the automatic crop lands on the middle of the photo, leaving Sophia's face just above the top edge.</p>

        <p>He taps <strong>⤢ Reposition photo (fix cropping)</strong>, sees his full photo on the left, and drags the dot up onto Sophia's face. The preview on the right snaps to a banner with her face centered and clear. He taps <strong>Save position</strong>. The hero on sophiasmith.com now opens on her face — exactly the first thing he wanted family to see.</p>

        <p>Five seconds, no re-cropping, no re-uploading. Just the right photo, framed the right way.</p>

